            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this pediatric BMI percentile calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Body mass index (BMI) in children and teens is interpreted using
                <strong>BMI-for-age percentiles</strong>. Instead of fixed
                cut-offs (as in adults), your child’s BMI is compared with a
                reference population of children of the same age and sex.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">BMI formula</p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  In metric units: \[ \text{BMI} = \frac{\text{weight
                  (kg)}}{\left(\text{height (m)}\right)^2} \]
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  In US / imperial units: \[ \text{BMI} = \frac{\text{weight
                  (lb)}}{\left(\text{height (in)}\right)^2} \times 703 \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                After BMI is calculated, the tool estimates the
                <strong>BMI-for-age percentile</strong> using smoothed reference
                curves derived from widely used international growth charts
                (such as CDC and WHO). The percentile tells you what proportion
                of children of the same age and sex have a lower BMI.
              </p>

              <h3>Interpreting pediatric BMI percentiles</h3>
              <p>
                Commonly used categories for children and teens (2–20 years)
                are:
              </p>
              <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                <thead>
                  <tr class="bg-gray-100">
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      BMI-for-age percentile
                    </th>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Category
                    </th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      &lt; 5th percentile
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Underweight
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      5th to &lt; 85th percentile
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Healthy weight
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      85th to &lt; 95th percentile
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">Overweight</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      &ge; 95th percentile
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">Obesity</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>

              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
                Some guidelines also define <strong>severe obesity</strong> as
                BMI &ge; 120% of the 95th percentile or BMI &ge; 35 kg/m²,
                whichever is lower. This calculator does not classify severe
                obesity; such assessments should be made by a pediatric
                specialist.
              </p>

              <h2>Step-by-step: using the pediatric BMI calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter age</strong> in years (2–20). You can use
                  decimals (e.g. 7.5 years).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Select sex</strong> (male or female), as BMI
                  percentiles differ by sex.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose units</strong>:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <strong>Metric</strong> – enter height in centimeters and
                      weight in kilograms.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <strong>US / Imperial</strong> – enter height in feet and
                      inches, weight in pounds.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Click <strong>“Calculate Pediatric BMI”</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  Review the <strong>BMI value</strong>,
                  <strong>percentile</strong>, and
                  <strong>weight category</strong>.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Limitations and important considerations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  BMI does not directly measure body fat and can be affected by
                  muscle mass, body build, and ethnicity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Rapid changes in percentile (up or down) may be more important
                  than a single value.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For children under 2 years,
                  <strong>weight-for-length</strong> charts are usually
                  preferred over BMI.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For children with chronic illnesses, disabilities, or very
                  high athletic training, BMI may be less reliable.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
                Always discuss any concerns about your child’s growth,
                nutrition, or weight with a pediatrician or other qualified
                health professional.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is a high BMI percentile always a problem?</h3>
              <p>
                Not necessarily. A high percentile suggests that a child has a
                higher BMI than most peers, but it does not by itself diagnose
                obesity or a health problem. Clinicians also consider growth
                history, family patterns, diet, physical activity, and any
                medical conditions.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can a child have a low BMI percentile and still be healthy?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Some children are naturally smaller or leaner. A low
                percentile may be normal for that child, especially if they have
                always tracked along a lower curve and are otherwise healthy and
                developing well. Sudden drops in percentile or other symptoms
                warrant medical review.
              </p>

              <h3>How often should I check my child’s BMI?</h3>
              <p>
                For most children, BMI is checked during routine health visits.
                At home, it’s usually enough to check occasionally rather than
                very frequently. Focus on long-term trends and healthy habits
                rather than single numbers.
              </p>

              <h3>
                What if the calculator result seems very different from my
                doctor’s chart?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Different countries and organizations use slightly different
                reference charts and methods. This tool provides an approximate
                percentile based on smoothed international references. If there
                is a discrepancy, your pediatrician’s measurement and
                interpretation should be considered authoritative.
              </p>

              <h3>How can I support a healthy weight for my child?</h3>
              <p>
                Emphasize balanced meals, regular physical activity, adequate
                sleep, and limiting sugary drinks and highly processed snacks.
                Avoid restrictive dieting in children unless specifically
                advised and supervised by a healthcare professional.
              </p>

              <p class="mt-4 text-xs text-gray-500">
                Educational use only. This calculator does not provide medical
                advice, diagnosis, or treatment.
              </p>
